    (1706, 23, 2025, 21, NULL, 10, NULL, 131, NULL, NULL, 'Q3 was during the General Assembly, which explains the spike.', 192, 'For both City Council & General Assembly legislation, BBMR has seen an uptick in the number of referrals for potential fiscal impact. Fiscal 2025 represented the beginning of this trend, we expect this to keep increasing.', 100, NULL, 2, '2026-06-26T16:54:00.998111', '2026-06-26T16:54:00.998111'),
    (1707, 24, 2025, NULL, NULL, NULL, NULL, 0, NULL, NULL, 'Data will be provided pending formal completion and publication of management research projects. This is an annualized measure due to timing/progression of projects.', 0, 'BBMR performed work on a number of larger management research reports that extended into Fiscal 2026. We anticipate an increased number of published reports in Fiscal 2026.', 3, NULL, 2, '2026-06-26T16:54:00.998111', '2026-06-26T16:54:00.998111'),
    (1708, 25, 2025, 0.005, NULL, 0.01, NULL, 0.016, NULL, NULL, 'BBMR anticipates closing Fiscal 2025 within the 2% Revenue Forecast Accuracy target.  As of the third quarter, BBMR projects a year-end surplus of $37.1 million, representing a 1.6% variance from the $2.3 billion Fiscal 2025 General Fund budget, excluding the use of Fund Balance._x000D_
_x000D_
Although certain revenue sources such as Investment Earnings (-$7.2 million), Camera Violations (-$4.4 million), Net Revenues from Parking Funds (-$3.7 million), and the Telecommunication Tax (-$1.3 million) are underperforming relative to budget assumptions, stronger than expected performance in the City’s labor and real estate markets has generated unanticipated receipts. These gains are expected not only to offset the revenue shortfalls but also to drive the projected surplus._x000D_
_x000D_
Stability in the City’s labor market has been reflected in the State''s income tax distributions. As of the third quarter, income tax revenues are projected to exceed budget by $15.2 million. Meanwhile, the City’s real estate market remains strong, with transaction volume up 1.0% and home values up 3.7% compared to last year. These favorable conditions support a projected $9.7 million surplus in Transfer and Recordation Taxes, with respective yield per transaction increases of 6.2% and 9.9% over budget assumptions._x000D_
_x000D_
Additional contributors to the projected $37.1 million surplus include:_x000D_
_x000D_
•	A $5.1 million surplus in Personal Property Taxes, driven by higher assessments of public utility providers and a greater number of certified businesses,_x000D_
_x000D_
•	Reduced costs from tax credits such as the Enterprise Zone ($3.1 million) and CHAP ($1.4 million),_x000D_
_x000D_
•	One-time unbudgeted revenues including $3.7 million in Miscellaneous Revenues, a $3.0 million Legal Settlement, and $2.8 million in delinquent Billboard Taxes._x000D_
_x000D_
Based on third-quarter projections, BBMR is confident in meeting its Fiscal 2025 performance target and remains committed to maintaining its 2.0% revenue forecast accuracy goal in future fiscal years._x000D_
_x000D_
_x000D_
_x000D_', 0.03, 'In Fiscal 2025, income tax revenue beat projections. This trend has continued into Fiscal 2026. The City is dependent on analysis and projections performed by the State.', 0.02, NULL, 2, '2026-06-26T16:54:00.998111', '2026-06-26T16:54:00.998111'),
    (1709, 26, 2025, 4.2, NULL, 4.1, NULL, 4.3, NULL, NULL, 'Quarterly data represents cumulative totals and resulting averages for BOE Submit turnaround (ex. Q2 is representative of performance across July 1-Dec 31, Q3 represents data across July 1-March 31). Overall performance is relatively consistent at each Quarter, at just above 4.0 days for analyst approval, though this trended in the wrong direction in the 3rd Quarter of FY25. There were a few significant outliers, in which several submissions were left unaddressed for two weeks or more. Common issues revolve around: input of incorrect account numbers by agency submittors, and limited understanding of relationship between the broader contract authority and annual budget authority. To mitigate this, we have been notifying analysts of specific instances that have significant duration, to prompt questions and next steps on what might be causing delay, and to ask to assistance if needed in order to avoid lengthy turnaround in future review. We will need to continually manage for the issue of BOE Submit deadlines (every two weeks); agency submittors and BBMR analysts alike may pattern submissions/approvals around these deadlines, versus consideration of normal time lapse.', 6.4, 'Within BOE Submit items cannot be sent back to users to make modifications once submitted, meaning items will remain pending with Analysts until an agency has resolved outstanding questions. BBMR continues to strive to move items quickly, but will always take additional time to ensure due diligence', 4, NULL, 2, '2026-06-26T16:54:00.998111', '2026-06-26T16:54:00.998111'),
    (1710, 27, 2025, 63, NULL, 82, NULL, 66, NULL, 50, NULL, 261, 'In FY2025, CHAP appraisal reviews fell 13% below projections, mainly because fewer applications were submitted due to a limited inventory of properties in areas preferred by developers in recent years, as well as uncertainty about local, state, and national economic conditions.', 300, 'It is anticipated that the number of appraisal reviews completed for the CHAP Tax Credit will continue to decline in FY25 due to economic reasons impacting the housing industry.', 2, '2026-06-26T16:54:00.998111', '2026-06-26T16:54:00.998111'),
    (1711, 28, 2025, 209, NULL, 113, NULL, 323, NULL, 99, NULL, 744, 'Fiscal 2025 data shows a slight increase in tax credit applications driven by new City developments.', 655, 'The number of tax credit applications received in FY2025 is expected to decrease due to various economic factors and insights from historical trends.', 2, '2026-06-26T16:54:00.998111', '2026-06-26T16:54:00.998111'),
    (1712, 29, 2025, 25, NULL, 21, NULL, 26, NULL, 101, NULL, 173, 'Fiscal 2025 data shows fewer tax credits rejected or revoked than projected, as applicants have become more familiar with qualification and eligibility requirements.', 220, 'There is an expectation that the number of rejected or revoked tax credits in FY2025 will decline, driven by the forecast of a reduced number of applications due to various economic factors and insights from historical trends.', 2, '2026-06-26T16:54:00.998111', '2026-06-26T16:54:00.998111'),
    (1713, 30, 2025, 3829639, NULL, 3723866, NULL, 4184086, NULL, -139889, 'The reduction is due to corrections to erroneous or improperly processed assessment increases being corrected by SDAT as well as one property-owner appeal that resulted in the reduction of a previous increase to a level more in line with the most recent sale value of the property._x000D_
_x000D_
_x000D_
_x000D_
As of 8/12/2025:_x000D_
_x000D_
•	10 properties have been issued first-level final notices after 7/1/2025, six of which included increased assessments._x000D_
_x000D_
•	147 FY2025 appeals remain without first-level final notices._x000D_
_x000D_
•	There remain 256 FY2025 appeals that have received final notices, which were appealed to PTAAB, 79 of which are awaiting hearings.', 11597700, 'Fiscal 2025 data reflects the results of the 1/1/2024 Assessment Appeals, which captured residual market value increases following the pandemic-driven market surge. This led to a success rate and outcomes that significantly exceeded original estimates.', 4390000, 'The 1/1/2024 Assessment Appeals (Fiscal Year 2025) will be of properties in Assessment Group 3, comprising the southern third of the City.  This Group has seen considerable growth in recent years and should see strong returns based on overall residential market growth over the last three years.  However, recent cooling in the residential market as interest rates have risen, combined with the continued impacts that COVID-19 has had on both Office and Retail properties, will likely temper the gains in this Group.  Revenue expectations should exceed the prior cycle, but by the slimmest of margins, and could be impacted dramatically if economic uncertainty in advance of the 2024 elections drives the market down further.', 2, '2026-06-26T16:54:00.998111', '2026-06-26T16:54:00.998111'),
    (1714, 31, 2025, 3302, NULL, 13, NULL, 17, NULL, 66, NULL, 3402, 'Fiscal 2025 data shows a slight increase in granted tax credit applications, primarily from new City residential developments.', 3355, 'The number of granted tax credits is expected to decrease, primarily due to the anticipation of receiving fewer applications, influenced by various economic factors.', 2, '2026-06-26T16:54:00.998111', '2026-06-26T16:54:00.998111'),
